This is a delete that first checks whether the type is complete. Similar to [`boost::checked_delete`](https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/release/libs/core/doc/html/core/checked_delete.html).

The idea of it is to generate a compilation error when attempting to delete an [incomplete type](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/type#Incomplete_type) ([which has a good chance of causing undefined behavior, depending on the type](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2517245/why-really-deleting-an-incomplete-type-is-undefined-behaviour)).

For example (using `boost::checked_delete` for convenience, since I don&#39;t know the specifics of the class of which your `delete_` is a member, but they&#39;re basically the same) :

    struct X;

    void foo(X* x) {
        boost::checked_delete(x);
    }

Note that a regular `delete x;` might cause a warning from the compiler (depending on your compiler), but that&#39;s not guaranteed.

