Your syntax isn&#39;t valid, as `push` must be on an instantiated object. Create the stack first, then push the Function, then add to queue.

    Function newFunc(funcName, funcExecept);
    Stack&lt;Function&gt; stack;
    stack.push( newFunc );
    processQueue.enqueue(stack);

or, put the stack of the queue first, then push to it

    processQueue.enqueue(Stack&lt;Function&gt;());
    processQueue.peekFront().push( Function( funcName, funcExecept ) );

In the second option, using `peekFront` assumes there&#39;s only one Stack in the queue, which is the one just added.

It&#39;s difficult to answer with exact syntax when we don&#39;t know the interface of your `Queue` and `Stack` classes, but here is how you could do it with the standard `std::queue` and `std::stack`:

```
std::queue&lt;std::stack&lt;Function&gt; processQueue;

// Add function to top of first stack of queue:
Function newFunc(funcName, funcExecept);
if (processQueue.empty())
  processQueue.push({}); // push an empty stack into the queue
processQueue.front().push(newFunc);

// Retrieve data:
processQueue.front().top().getName();
```

The function names will of course be different in your case (based on your class&#39; API), but the principle should be the same.

Note that unless you have a *strong* reason to use custom classes, you should use the standard containers instead; they&#39;re way more tested and optimised than custom implementations are ever likely to be.

